description:
Finally the debate is over: size matters, and women prefer men with larger packages because it predicts a man's sex appeal, according to a new study in the journal Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences (PNAS). The study, conducted by the Australian National University, revealed that the taller the man, the bigger the effect his penis size had on his sex appeal. The group of researchers showed life-size, computer-generated figures of men that varied in body shape, height, and penis size to 105 women. The females then rated the figures' sexual attractiveness. The findings showed that women preferred taller men with broader shoulders and narrow hips (V-shaped, instead of pear-shaped), which supports earlier research. However, this study indicates that penis size is also relevant. Outcomes showed: the bigger, the better. Females documented the most appealing penis size was even bigger than the researchers tested, surpassing the penis size of 98% of Italian males. Professor Jennions said, "We've found that penis size did influence a man's sex appeal, and it was just as important as height, which is a well-known factor in male attractiveness." The study also noted that larger penises are ideal but were much more attractive on taller men than shorter men. "To put it bluntly, if you are short and pear-shaped, a large penis is not going to increase your attractiveness," Dr Mautz said...

description: Ensignbus had their Routemaster coach RMC1485 parked up at Leytonstone on Thursday 7th June. It was used for crew breaks, but also ran in service during the morning peak (as it has platform doors, it can be Driver-only operated). An emergency rail replacement service operated between Stratford and Leytonstone from the afternoon of Wednesday 6th June until the following afternoon. This was following flooding of the tunnel between Stratford and Mile End, which closed the Central Line between Bethnal Green and Leytonstone. Ensignbus have considerable experience in operating both pre-planned and emergency Rail Replacement services, and had overall responsibility for co-ordinating the Stratford-Leytonstone service. The RMCs were specifically designed for Green Line coach work, featuring twin headlamps, more comfortable seating, luggage racks and power-operated platform doors. RMC 1485 was delivered to London Transport's Country Bus Division in 1962 and allocated to Windsor Garage for route 718. It passed to London Country Bus Services Ltd. on 1st January 1970 when the Country Bus Division was transferred to the National Bus Company and was demoted to ordinary bus work in 1972. It then worked from a number of different Garages until it was withdrawn in 1980, whereupon it was bought back by London Transport for use as a Driver Trainer. In 1989 it made an unexpected return to express bus work, being one of a number transferred to Upton Park garage to work a new Commuter Express route X15 from the newly-developing Beckton area to Oxford Circus. When this service was withdrawn, superceded by the Docklands Light Railway, the bus remained at Upton Park for route 15 and passed into Stagecoach ownership in September 1994. It was withdrawn on conversion of route 15 to Driver-only in August 2003, passing to Lothian Regional Transport (Edinburgh) for its Mac Tours operation. Ensignbus acquired the vehicle for its private hire fleet in February 2009. www.ensignbushire.com/?page_id=932

description:
A scene about to pass into history. First's DML 41427 shows the distinctive rear rake of its Marshall body as it loads up at Stratford City during the afternoon of Friday 16th September. It has also managed to retain its original livery, featuring the yellow-and-white stripes that First adopted for London operations until the decision to go all-red. 

Stratford City only opened on Tuesday 13th September, so First operated route D8 here for just four days. 

All this is about to be swept away, as from Saturday 17th September Go-Ahead London will take over this route with brand new Enviro200 Darts. As this bus is now ten years old it is unlikely it will see further service in London. However the Marshall bodywork will not quite disappear from the streets of East London as route 309 will retain the type until March 2012, and the odd example will still find its way to Stratford City on route 339. 

I wonder, has anyone thought of preserving one of these?

description: 1932AD, 26 May, House of Lords, London. The House of Lords gives judgment on the Donoghue's case. The case involved Mrs Donoghue who had had a drink including ginger beer in a cafe in Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland. A decomposed snail was in the bottle. She fell ill, and then sued the ginger beer manufacturer, Mr Stevenson. After two earlier hearings - in the outer and then inner Court, Mrs Donoghue filled a petition to The House of Lords. They held that the manufacturer owed a duty of care to her, which was breached, because it was reasonably foreseeable that failure to ensure the product's safety would lead to harm of consumers. This case is of importance in English and Scottish law as it established the modern law of negligence and established the neighbour test. In this MOC I have used a frog in the place of a snail. Built for the competition over on brickfanatics.

description: 22nd November 2011 at National Theatre (Djanogly Concert Pitch), London SE1. Free Foyer Music. Country: Britain. Style: Jazz - Modern. Lineup: Duck Baker (g), Alex Ward (clarinet), Joe Williamson (b). Duck Baker (Richard R. Baker IV) is a fingerstyle guitarist from Riichmond, Virginia. He lived in Europe 1978-89 and again from 2005 (currently in Reading). description:
4th August 2012 at Exhibition Road, London SW7.

Part of ”Exhibition Road Show”, a Festival to celebrate the London Olympics (free event).

Country: Canada. Style: Wind Band / Pipe & Drum Band.

Lineup: (Wind Ensemble) Flutes, Clarinets, Bass Clarinet, Bassoon, Saxophones, Trumpets, French Horns, Alto Horns, Tuba, Double Bass, (Pipe & Drum Band) Highland Bagpipes, Tenor Drums, Bass Drum.

St Andrew’s College is a boys-only private boarding school in Aurora, Ontario. The musicians were in London for various events around the Olympic Games. The Wind Ensemble was chosen to represent Canada after winning an award in the Concert Band category for schools and universities at MusicFest Canada in 2010. They were joined for the trip by 11 members of the larger Pipe and Drum Band. The school is connected to the Gordon Highlanders via the 48th Highlanders of Canada and the School Cadets Corps, and wear the Gordon tartan. The repertoire included Maple Leaf Forever, Scotland the Brave, the anthem from the 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver, pipe tunes, and a medley of hits by Michael Bublé.

London-born Barry Martyn first visited New Orleans in 1961 and has lived there since 1984. description: 4th September 2017 at St Thomas’ Hospital (Central Hall), London SE1. Guy’s and St Thomas’ Lunchtime Performances (free event) / Totally Thames festival. Country: Britain. Style: Original material inspired by Folk, World Music and Jazz. Lineup: Fiona Fey (v/ clarinet), Laura Inskip (v/clarinet), Rey Yusuf (v/drums), Anna Lowenstein (fiddle), Kai Carter (g), Robyn Hemmings (b). The band began as an acapella trio, added a fiddle (with a background in Classical Music and Klezmer) while the others started using instruments, and now often perform as a six piece. The lyrics produce new and recreated folk tales. I have photographed bassist Robyn Hemmings twice before with Nalmo and with Yaz Fentazi (www.flickr.com/photos/kmlivemusic/tags/robynhemmings,-tel...). More information: www.telltaletusk.com/, www.facebook.com/TellTaleTusk/.

description:
Taiko, Japanese Traditional Drum

Japanese taiko drums have been developed into a wide range of percussion instruments that are used in both Japanese folk and classical musical traditions.

Early History

According to myth, taiko was started by Ame no Uzume, a shaman-like female deity. One day, fed up with her cruel younger brother, the sun goddess, Amaterasu, hid herself in a cave. The world became pitch dark and the other deities tried to appease Amaterasu, so that world be bright again. They held a big party in front of the cave and Ame no Uzume danced an erotic dance, stamping her feet on a wooden tub. The gods laughed and cheered loudly and the noise provoked Amaterasu to come out her cave. And thus, the world saw light again.

In feudal Japan, taiko were often used to motivate troops, to help set a marching pace, and to call out orders or announcements. Approaching or entering a battle, the taiko yaku (drummer) was responsible for setting the marching pace.

The View

Taken during the night carnival in Thames London Festival 2011, near Victoria Embankment by Thames.
